               <head>Majma' al-nafa'is, selections</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Intikhāb-i majmaʿ al-nafāʾis by Āsā Rām</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2010105563 http://lccn.loc.gov/n90719617 http://lccn.loc.gov/n2013068356 http://lccn.loc.gov/n50002518 http://lccn.loc.gov/n89215273 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2010106697" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_4015-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="person_f7657">Āsā Rām</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="per" key="person_f7657" type="supplied">آسا رام</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_21949">Intikhāb-i majmaʿ al-nafāʾis</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_21949">انتخاب مجمع النّفائس</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>No formal title stated in the work</p>
                        <p>Selection from the larger Persian biographical dictionary of poets (with quotations of verses), the Majmaʿ al-nifāʾis of Sirāj al-Dīn ʿAlī Khān "Ārzū," apparently ordered by the Timurid or Mughal Emperor Shāh ʿĀlam in regnal year 4 (1177 / 1763), possibly while in Bengal, under the vice-regency of the Navvāb-Nāẓim Qāsim ʿAlī Khān</p>
                        <p>Consists of approximately 200 entries, mostly of poets connected with South Asia, extending from a-y: "Ījād" to "Yaktā"</p>
                        <p>Preface differs from other standard editions</p>
                        <p>The compilor or epitomaton is not mentioned. However, a note on the title page in the hand of William Irvine states, "Āsā Rām made this abridgement"</p>
                        <p>Not dated</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per" xml:lang="per">Persian</textLang>
